Recall about the main steps of discriminant analysis:¶

  • estimation of weights pi_1 and pi_2 for each class,
  • estimation of empirical means mu_1 and mu_2 for each class,
  • estimation of empirical covariance matrices sigma_1 and sigma_2,
  • computation of the common averaged covariance sigma (average of intra-class covariances),
  • computation of log-probabilities of belonging to each class,
  • decision of classification,
  • display results.
In [9]:
def weight(data,clas,dim_clas): # input: - training data 
                                #        -the class for which we want the weight 
                                #        -in which column of the training data we can find the label (class)
    return len(data[data[:,dim_clas]==clas])/len(data) 
def means(data,clas):# input: - training data 
                     #        -the class for which we want the mean
    return np.array([np.mean(data[data[:,0]==clas][:,1]),np.mean(data[data[:,0]==clas][:,2])])
def sigma(data,clas):# input: - training data 
                     #        -the class for which we want the cov matrix
    return np.cov(data[data[:,0]==clas][:,1],data[data[:,0]==clas][:,2])
def com_avg_cov(data,T_class):# input: - training data 
                              #        -a list of the classes we got
                              # returns: - avg weighted covariance matrix of all the classes
    clas1=T_class[0]
    clas2=T_class[1]
    sigma_1=sigma(data,clas1)
    sigma_2=sigma(data,clas2)
    res=np.zeros((len(T_class),len(T_class)))
    for i in T_class:
        res+=weight(data,i,0)*sigma(data,i)
    return res
def log_proba_LDA(data,T_class,x): # Returns a list of probabilities (log Probabilities)
                                   # where the P (log P) of belonging to a class K is at the Kth position.
                                   # All this using the avg cov matrix of all the classes
    X=np.array(x)
    W=np.zeros(len(T_class))
    MU=[]
    SIGMA=com_avg_cov(data,T_class)
    frac=[]
    for i in range(len(T_class)):
        W[i]=weight(data,T_class[i],0)
        MU.append(means(train,T_class[i]))
        frac.append(W[i]*np.exp(-.5*(X-MU[i]).dot(np.linalg.inv(SIGMA).dot((X-MU[i]).T))))
    P=frac/np.sum(frac)
    return P,np.log(P)
def log_proba_QDA(data,T_class,x):  # Returns a list of probabilities (log Probabilities)
                                   # where the P (log P) of belonging to a class K is at the Kth position.
                                   # All this using the cov matrix of each class
    X=np.array(x)
    W=np.zeros(len(T_class))
    MU=[]
    SIGMA=[]
    frac=[]
    for i in range(len(T_class)):
        W[i]=weight(data,T_class[i],0)
        MU.append(means(train,T_class[i]))
        SIGMA.append(sigma(data,T_class[i]))
        frac.append(W[i]*np.exp(-.5*(X-MU[i]).dot(np.linalg.inv(SIGMA[i]).dot((X-MU[i]).T))))
    P=frac/np.sum(frac)
    return P,np.log(P)
def decision(data,T_class,x,mode):# input: - training data 
                                  #        - a list of the classes we have in the training set
                                  #        - the 2D dot to classify
                                  #        - using LDA or QDA 
    if mode=='LDA':
        return T_class[log_proba_LDA(data,T_class,x)[0].argmax()]
    elif mode=='QDA':
        return T_class[log_proba_QDA(data,T_class,x)[0].argmax()]

But what happens if we had another training set ? one can easily imagine that the KNN classifier will be largely impacted, but what for the two others for which the weights, means, and covariances of each of the classes will change?

To answer this question and build more robust conclusions, we will bootstrap the training data (resample with replacement) a certain number of times

Bootstraping and comparing the performance asymptotically:¶

In [39]:
def resample_with_replacement(train):
    bs_train=[]
    for i in range(len(train)):
        bs_train.append(random.choice(train))
    return np.array(bs_train)

time: 520 µs

For time issues, we will boostrap the training data $100$ times

we will test on the same test set.

In [40]:
errQDA=[]
errLDA=[]
errKNN=[]
N_experiences=100
for i in range(N_experiences):
    bs=resample_with_replacement(train)
    CLDA=[]
    CQDA=[]
    for dot in test[:,1:]:
        CLDA.append(decision(bs,[1,2],dot,"LDA"))
        CQDA.append(decision(bs,[1,2],dot,"QDA"))
    TLDA=1*(np.array(CLDA)==test[:,0])
    TQDA=1*(np.array(CQDA)==test[:,0])
    errLDA.append(1-(np.count_nonzero(TLDA)/len(test)))
    errQDA.append(1-(np.count_nonzero(TQDA)/len(test)))
    cv_scores = []
    neighbors=range(1,31)
    for k in neighbors:
        knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
        scores = cross_val_score(knn, bs[:,1:], bs[:,0], cv=10, scoring='accuracy')
        cv_scores.append(scores.mean())
    MSE = [1 - x for x in cv_scores]

    # determining best k
    optimal_k = neighbors[MSE.index(min(MSE))]
    neigh = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=optimal_k)
    neigh.fit(bs[:,1:], bs[:,0])
    class_pred=neigh.predict(test[:,1:])
    T=test[:,0]-class_pred
    T1=T[T!=0]
    errKNN.append(len(T1)/len(test))

  • As we said in the start, KNN classifier has a quiet big misclassification error variance. But that may be because it is very dependant of the chosen value of $K_{optimal}$: when cross-validating, it may happen that the training/cross validation set has some redundant records ( when bootstraping we resample with replacement), and thus the K resulting of the cros validation may not be the best one for the generalisation
  • LDA is situated between the QDA and KNN but has a similar behavior as the QDA. (Stability)

Multiclass datasets:¶

We wrap all the previous defined functions for LDA and QDA into one that outputs a dictionnary with all the results:

  • indices : Classes in the training set that we input
  • pi: The weights of each population in the training set
  • mu: The mean of each population in the training set
  • Sigma: the avg cov matrix
  • Alpha: the inverse of the avg cov matrix
  • Probability Result for the Specified label: the probability that X belong to the class K given as an input
  • Probabilities: an array of probabilities of belonging to a class i in the ith position
  • Classification result: The class to which X belongs
In [42]:
def Classifier(X,train,K, Algorithm):
    Training = train.copy()
    labels=np.unique(Training[:,0])
    assert K in labels 
    N = Training.shape[0]
    D ={}
    D['indices']=list(labels)
    D['pi']= [np.count_nonzero(train[:,0]== i) / N for i in labels]
    D['mu']= [np.mean(Training[Training[:,0]== i][:,1:], axis =0) for i in labels]
    D['Y'] = X-np.array(D['mu'])
    Sigmas= [np.cov(Training[Training[:,0]== i][:,1], Training[Training[:,0]== i][:,2]) for i in labels]
    if (Algorithm == "LDA"):

        D['Sigma']= sum([D['pi'][k] *  Sigmas[k] for k in range(len(labels))],axis =0)
        D['Alpha'] =np.linalg.inv(D['Sigma'])
        IntermediateResults = [D['pi'][i] * np.exp(-0.5 * np.dot(D['Y'][i] ,np.dot(D['Alpha'],D['Y'][i]))) for i in range(len(labels))]
        D['Probabilities'] = IntermediateResults / np.sum(np.array(IntermediateResults))
    elif (Algorithm == "QDA"):
        D['sigmas']= Sigmas

        D['Alphas'] =[np.linalg.inv(sigma) for sigma in D['sigmas']] 
        IntermediateResults= [D['pi'][i] * np.exp(-0.5 * np.dot(D['Y'][i] ,np.dot(D['Alphas'][i],D['Y'][i]))) for i in range(len(labels))]
        D['Probabilities'] = IntermediateResults / np.sum(np.array(IntermediateResults))
        
    D['Probability Result for the Specified label'] =D['Probabilities'][list(labels).index(K)] 
    D['Classification Result']= int(labels[D['Probabilities'].argmax()])
    return D

Optical Recognition of Handwritten Digits Data Set
===================================================

Notes
-----
Data Set Characteristics:
    :Number of Instances: 5620
    :Number of Attributes: 64
    :Attribute Information: 8x8 image of integer pixels in the range 0..16.
    :Missing Attribute Values: None
    :Creator: E. Alpaydin (alpaydin '@' boun.edu.tr)
    :Date: July; 1998

This is a copy of the test set of the UCI ML hand-written digits datasets
http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Optical+Recognition+of+Handwritten+Digits

The data set contains images of hand-written digits: 10 classes where
each class refers to a digit.

Preprocessing programs made available by NIST were used to extract
normalized bitmaps of handwritten digits from a preprinted form. From a
total of 43 people, 30 contributed to the training set and different 13
to the test set. 32x32 bitmaps are divided into nonoverlapping blocks of
4x4 and the number of on pixels are counted in each block. This generates
an input matrix of 8x8 where each element is an integer in the range
0..16. This reduces dimensionality and gives invariance to small
distortions.

For info on NIST preprocessing routines, see M. D. Garris, J. L. Blue, G.
T. Candela, D. L. Dimmick, J. Geist, P. J. Grother, S. A. Janet, and C.
L. Wilson, NIST Form-Based Handprint Recognition System, NISTIR 5469,
1994.

References
----------
  - C. Kaynak (1995) Methods of Combining Multiple Classifiers and Their
    Applications to Handwritten Digit Recognition, MSc Thesis, Institute of
    Graduate Studies in Science and Engineering, Bogazici University.
  - E. Alpaydin, C. Kaynak (1998) Cascading Classifiers, Kybernetika.
  - Ken Tang and Ponnuthurai N. Suganthan and Xi Yao and A. Kai Qin.
    Linear dimensionalityreduction using relevance weighted LDA. School of
    Electrical and Electronic Engineering Nanyang Technological University.
    2005.
  - Claudio Gentile. A New Approximate Maximal Margin Classification
    Algorithm. NIPS. 2000.

Conclusion

As strange as it may looks (except if there is an error in the code but we do not think so...) KNN algorithm performs better on a multiclass 2D problem. But QDA remains the most stable method among them.

What we conclude from all this is:

  • if we have a 2D dimensional problem: Binary ==> use QDA || multiclass ==> use KNN with K determined by cross validation

But KNN is not always the adequate solution as it fails to perform well in high dimentional problems as told in the course. ( We may not always want to use dimensional reduction because by doing so we lose interpretation of data and we become kind of "blindtrusting" what the algorithm returns)

To confirm this, lets apply LDA, QDA and KNN for the iris data directly without dimension reduction ( directly on 4-D space) with bootstraping training data.

def DRAW_LDA(polydegree,train,test): # a function that takes as an input the rank of the polynomial degree we want to see
                                     # training set and test set
                                     # Returns: a plot of the decisio boundary and the misclassification error
    poly_features = PolynomialFeatures(polydegree,include_bias=False)
    Dataset = np.vstack((train,test))
    x = poly_features.fit_transform(Dataset[:,1:])
    Dataset_ =np.hstack((Dataset,x[:,2:]))
    train,test = Dataset_[:99,:],Dataset_[100:,:]
    clf = LinearDiscriminantAnalysis()
    clf.fit(train[:,1:], train[:,0])
    GRID=[]
    for x in x1:
        for y in x2:
            dot=poly_features.fit_transform([[x,y]])
            cl= clf.predict(dot)
            GRID.append([cl,x,y])
    GRID=np.array(GRID)
    Error = 1 - count_nonzero(clf.predict(test[:,1:]) == test[:,0])/len(test)
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,7))
    plt.xlabel("X")
    plt.ylabel("Y")
    plt.scatter(GRID[GRID[:,0]==1][:,1],GRID[GRID[:,0]==1][:,2], color="r",label="LDA Class 1 domain",marker=".")
    plt.scatter(GRID[GRID[:,0]==2][:,1],GRID[GRID[:,0]==2][:,2], color="b",label="LDA Class 2 domain",marker=".")
    plt.scatter(train[train[:,0]==1][:,1],train[train[:,0]==1][:,2], color="r")
    plt.scatter(train[train[:,0]==2][:,1],train[train[:,0]==2][:,2], color="b")
    plt.title("Boundary LDA(degree polynomial " +str(polydegree)+") and training set || error on test = "+str(Error))
    plt.legend();
